  volume = {2},
  abstract = {The Sierra Nevada is a c. 4000 m range of mountains parallel to the North American Pacific Coast that was repeatedly glaciated during the climatic fluctuations of the Quaternary. The glacial record on the eastern side of the range includes eight named Pleistocene glaciations and stadials: McGee, Sherwin, Casa Diablo, Mono Basin, Tahoe, Tenaya, Tioga and Recess Peak, as well as the Neoglacial Matthes (Little Ice Age) advance (all in order of decreasing age). Studies of lake-sediment cores show that the actual number of glacial advances and retreats was much greater than nine, although not all glaciers left drift that has been preserved and/or identified in the mountains themselves. End-moraine positions and equilibrium-line altitude (ELA) depressions of the largest glaciers were about the same, regardless of age. Recent efforts to date glacial deposits numerically have added detail to our understanding of Sierra Nevada glacial chronology. However, except for the late-Pleistocene advances, the results may serve only as limits to the age of the glaciations, because of erosion and other geological complexities.},
